While tenecteplase is sometimes used off-label in acute ischemic stroke and has shown some promise in improving reperfusion and functional outcomes in certain populations, there is no strong level-one evidence demonstrating superiority over alteplase. Key guidelines state that alteplase remains the only FDA-approved thrombolytic for ischemic stroke, and while tenecteplase may serve as a reasonable alternative under specific circumstances, it lacks definitive support for routine use. Therefore, tirilazad—being unrelated to tenecteplase and not mentioned in any evidence—is neither studied nor recommended.

